@G[c3 stills_73.png]@L
		@H Historical Background @L
		Tarraco had been inhabited by Iberian natives and Greco-Phoenician traders since its founding in the 5th century BC. Its name likely stems from the tall cliff on which a major part of the city stood. @L@L
		In the year 270 BC, Roman armies arrived in Hispania and claimed Tarraco for their base of operations, swiftly turning it into a major weapons manufacturing center and a supply hub. @L@L
		At this time, Rome had solidified its grip on southern Italy and turned towards Sicily, where another ancient superpower, the state of Carthage, held significant territories. Carthago was originally established as a Phoenician colony benefiting greatly from its superb location in North Africa (modern day Tunisia). It offered opportunities to control trade in the Mediterranean Sea. @L@L
		During the first millennium BC, it developed into a capital of the Punic Empire. After the First Punic War ended, the empire collapsed and gave rise to a republic and a new system of government. Like Greek or Roman political systems at the time, the democracy of ancient times would be much closer to a modern-day oligarchy. @L@L
		Carthage would remain a major threat to Roman influence and the war would return twice more in the future, leaving Rome eventually triumphant as the sole power in the Mediterranean region.@L@L 
		
		@G[c3 instructions icon.png]	
		@H Instructions @L
		Welcome to Hispania governor. The city of Tarraco is now under our control and the task now falls to you to turn it into a major manufacturing hub and supply base for future Iberian expeditions. You will not directly take part in any active warfare, for you only need to supply Roman officers with ample provisions as the land around the city is incredibly fertile. @L@L
		Thanks to the winding rivers depositing rich sediments in the soil around Tarraco, you can expect bountiful harvests of wheat and other products. Another valuable local commodity is the marble which can be quarried for both local use and profitable export. Unfortunately, there are no suitable veins of iron ore within the city limits, so you will need to bring in iron ingots for your arms workshops via trade. A report from the initial Roman expedition indicated that there may be a way to extract iron, but the required workforce does not suit the small nature of the initial settlement. Perhaps later you will be able to establish large scale mining operations. @L@L
		The terrain in Tarraco will prove the most challenging you have dealt with thus far, but with your experience, governor, you will surely thrive even in the rugged environment of Hispania. @L@L
		
