		@H Historical Background @L
		Romans were quite advanced for their time in terms of mining technology and knowledge. Many large-scale mines were developed to fuel the economy as well as provide jobs in large scale projects. Some large mines and plantations would also be fully staffed by slave labor. @L@L
		This resulted in a crisis and was one of the reasons why the Late Republic had many societal issues. Rich aristocrats would buy land from farmers in Italy and buy out any competition to their operations, eradicating small farms and forcing the population into cities which swelled. @L@L
		Many of these people would have no skills in craftsmanship and would become fully dependent on the Roman free-food program called the "grain dole". @L@L
		This increased the tension in Roman society and meant that if state granaries ran low on grain, massive riots and unrest would soon follow. Maintaining large scale stockpiles and expanding Roman territory was therefore vital for its continuous survival. @L@L
		Julius Caesar, who led a reform faction during the Late Republic, proposed much legislation during his year as consul. Some of it was exclusively targeted at expanding the grain dole and buying out unprofitable plantations to redistribute land back to the urban poor, via lottery. @L@L
		This was met with resentment from the conservative faction which had a vested interest in keeping the status quo and not addressing any of these issues. This eventually boiled over when Caesar completed his conquest of Gaul. The Senate, led by the conservatives refused to ratify the conquest, give veterans their land handout as retirement payment, and demanded his resignation despite prior legislation that gave him permission to retain his command and provinces for an extended duration. @L@L
		As mentioned before, this was a precursor to the eventual civil war, when political factionalism would break the Roman political system. @L@L@L@L

