		@H Historical Background @L
		Roman armor evolved in similar fashion to their weaponry and organization as they encountered new enemies and adapted. Some of the armor used during specific periods were: @L@L
		Bronze or boiled-leather muscle cuirass, @lorica @musculata - First appeared in late Archaic Greece and became widespread throughout the 5th and 4th centuries BC. It was later used by Romans for generals or emperors as it depicted optimal muscle physique. @L@L
		Iron chainmail armor, @lorica @hamata - Romans learned of this invention from Celts living in northern Italy. Very robust armor that was very labor intensive to produce, offered great overall protection and flexibility. Starting kit of Late Republic legionaries. @L@L
		Iron or steel banded armor, @lorica @segmentata - Also called lorica lamminata, its introduction is not exactly known. Some argue that it was introduced after Crassusâ€™ defeat by the Parthians in the year 53 BC, while others argue that it was after a revolt in 21 AD. This armor is overused in popular media and would not reflect the armor used by most Roman soldiers during times of Caesar or even Augustus. It was not unique to the Romans, as Parthians and other eastern people used similar banded armor even before the Romans adopted it. @L@L
		Scale mail armor, @lorica @squamata - Used mostly during the decline of the Western Roman Empire and by Byzantine armies. It falls short of other armor, but its main advantage was lower production costs, fitting well into the environment where Rome was in heavy decline and could not afford to arm or equip its troops with quality equipment. It still served its purpose and was not worthless by any means. @L@L@L@L

